@node "usage" "usage"
@{b}@{u}USAGE@{ub}@{uu}

  To use Genos Mind Machine, darken the room with your Amiga in it, turn on
some soothing music if you are so inclined, and double-click the icon. The
program will begin to load. At the main menu, select the level of brain
stimulation you are interested in. @{"Refer to Brain Freq." link "theory" 0}

  At Level 1 you will be beginning to relax. The following levels will start
at Level 1 and gradully change into a deeper state of relaxation. By the
time you reach Level 4, you will have been watching your screen for quite
awhile so be patient, and think about relaxing.

  If you will notice, there are dots in the background of the flashing
screens. Just focus on these dots and allow the flashing to do its job.

  The Registered Version will also contain sound waves through your Amigas
speaker(s) to help achieve these states faster.

  How often to use the program is up to you, but please be careful. I am NOT
responsible for anything that happens as a result of using this program.
Please use some common sense, as with anything else.

 IF YOU SUFFER FROM SEIZURES OR EPILEPSY, PLEASE DO NOT USE THIS SOFTWARE!!
@endnode

@node "health" "health"
@{b}@{u}HEALTH WARNING!!@{ub}@{uu}

    This  product  is  not  guaranteed  to  reduce  mental illness or
otherwise decrease  the  number  of epileptic seizures the user may
experience.  In fact, tests  indicate  that  the  incidence  of  severe
epileptic attacks in users of MindMachine is at least 1 in 200,000.

    Further,  it  is not advised that MindMachine be used after a meal,
after or before  ingesting  a  MAO  inhibitor, after a period of stress,
during illness, before sleep, in the morning, or even at any other time in
particular.
@endnode

@node "author" "author"
@{b}@{u}ABOUT ME@{ub}@{uu}

  I am 34 year old former Police Officer who had to find a "safer" way to
make a living. I started out on a Texas Instruments 99/4A many years ago
before moving to a Commodore 64. Eventually, I saved enough to get an Amiga
500, before finally getting a "beefed up" Amiga 2000.

  Trained in Electronic Engineering Technology through Cleveland Institute
of Electronics, am currently employed by BMG. Specializing in compact disk
mastering, pre-mastering, and manufacturing.

  Have used most of the computers from the Sperry Univac to the newest
Pentium machines, nothing still even compares to the AMIGA for
cross-platformability!!!
@endnode

